# Image Upload Feature for Crop Advisory

This plan outlines the steps to implement an image upload feature allowing farmers to upload pictures of their crops alongside their query for more accurate advice.

## Proposed Changes

### Backend Updates

#### [MODIFY] [server/index.js](file:///d:/project/AI-Powered%20Local%20Crop%20Advisory%20System/server/index.js)
- Update `express.json()` middleware to increase the request body size limit (e.g., to '10mb' or '50mb') to accommodate base64-encoded image payloads.
- Update the `/api/advise` endpoint to destructure `image` (an object containing `inlineData` with base64 `data` and `mimeType`) from `req.body` in addition to the `prompt`.
- Modify the Gemini API call to pass an array `[systemInstruction, image]` to `generateContent` if an image is provided.
- Adjust the `systemInstruction` slightly to prompt the AI to analyze the provided image if present.

### Frontend Updates

#### [MODIFY] [client/src/App.jsx](file:///d:/project/AI-Powered%20Local%20Crop%20Advisory%20System/client/src/App.jsx)
- Introduce new state variables `selectedImage` (File object) and `imagePreview` (base64 data URL).
- Add an `<input type="file" accept="image/*" />` to the UI, likely styled as an icon button next to the microphone.
- Implement a helper function to convert the selected file to a base64 `Promise` via `FileReader`.
- Update the UI to display a thumbnail of the `imagePreview` with a clear button to remove it.
- Modify the [getAdvisory](file:///d:/project/AI-Powered%20Local%20Crop%20Advisory%20System/client/src/App.jsx#75-102) function to include the base64 string and its mime-type in the JSON request body sent to the backend.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. Open the web app and write a query without an image to ensure the old functionality still works.
2. Select an image using the new upload button and ensure the thumbnail preview renders correctly.
3. Submit a query with the image (e.g., "What is wrong with these leaves?") and verify the AI responds based on the visual context.
4. Verify error handling for files that are too large or unsupported formats.
